{"questionId":"22669715","questionHtml":"<p>Using your answers from part (c), show that phase portrait trajectories close to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> may be given by the equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math> is a positive constant.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math></p>\n<p>(e.g. any attempt to substitute their solutions to part (c))&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> There will probably be lots of students who assume what is to be proved by introducing a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math> earlier on. Do not penalize this.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>attempting to isolate <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>B</mi><mi>y</mi></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac></math>&nbsp;<strong>OR</strong>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>A</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22669715","referenceCode":"24M.3.AHL.TZ2.2di","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Using your answers from part (c), show that phase portrait trajectories close to A may be given by the equation x3y2=k, where k is a positive constant.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.14—Setting up a DE, solve by separating variables"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}